You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and a **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with the cancel command and dirty flag

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Cancel()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard) return;
        }

        HasUnsavedChanges = false; // prevent the guard from firing too
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Navigation guard in `AppShell.xaml.cs` (catches swipe-back / hardware back)

The custom button handles explicit taps, but users can also swipe back or press the hardware back button. Guard those with `OnNavigating`:

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("editproduct", typeof(EditProductPage));
    }

    protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
    {
        base.OnNavigating(args);

        // Only intercept back-navigation (Pop)
        if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
            return;

        // Check if the current page is EditProductPage
        if (Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
            && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
            && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Must defer so we can await the dialog
            var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

            bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                args.Cancel();

            deferral.Complete();
        }
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- **`args.Cancel()`** stops the navigation when the user chooses "Stay".
- The guard checks `args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so it only fires on back-navigation, not forward pushes.
- Setting `HasUnsavedChanges = false` in the `Cancel` command prevents the guard from double-prompting when `GoToAsync("..")` triggers the Pop.
